The probability that $n$ balls are in the box given that the first ball chosen was black is $\frac{1}{101} \cdot \frac{n}{100} \div \frac{1}{2} = \frac{n}{50 \cdot 101}$. Hence, the probability that there are $n$ balls and the second ball that rolls out is black given that the first ball that rolls out is black is $\frac{n}{50 \cdot 101} \cdot \frac{n-1}{99} = \frac{1}{50 \cdot 99 \cdot 101} \cdot n(n-1)$. Therefore, the desired probability is

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{50 \cdot 99 \cdot 101} \cdot \sum_{n=0}^{100} (n^2 - n)  &= \frac{1}{50\cdot99\cdot101}\cdot\left(\frac{100\cdot101\cdot201}{6}-\frac{100\cdot101}{2}\right) \\ &= \frac{2}{3}
\end{align*}Hence, $p+q = \boxed{5}$.

Notice that the probability that Jackson is at position $k+1$ after $n$ steps is $\binom{n}{k} \cdot 0.85^{n-k} \cdot 0.15^k$. Hence,

\begin{align*}
E_n &= \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{1}{k+1} \cdot \binom{n}{k} \cdot 0.85^{n-k} \cdot 0.15^k \\ &=  \sum_{k=0}^n \frac{n!}{(k+1)! \cdot (n-k)!} \cdot 0.85^{n-k} \cdot 0.15^k \\ &= \frac{1}{n+1} \cdot \sum_{k=0}^n  \binom{n+1}{k+1} \cdot 0.85^{n-k} \cdot 0.15^k \\ &= \frac{1}{0.15 \cdot (n+1)} \cdot \sum_{k=0}^n  \binom{n+1}{k+1} \cdot 0.85^{n-k} \cdot 0.15^{k+1} \\ &= \frac{1}{0.15 \cdot (n+1)} \cdot \left( -0.85^{n+1} + \sum_{k=-1}^n  \binom{n+1}{k+1} \cdot 0.85^{n-k} \cdot 0.15^{k+1} \right) \\ &= \frac{1}{0.15 \cdot (n+1)} \cdot \left( -0.85^{n+1} + 1 \right) \\ &= \frac{1-0.85^{n+1}}{0.15 \cdot (n+1)} \\ &= \frac{20^{n+1}-17^{n+1}}{3 \cdot 20^n \cdot (n+1)}
\end{align*}Notice that $n$ is going to be really large so we can get rid of the $17^{n+1}$ term: $\frac{20^{n+1}-17^{n+1}}{3 \cdot 20^n \cdot (n+1)} \approx \frac{20}{3 \cdot (n+1)}$. Then we have $\frac{3n+3}{20} > 2017 \implies n >13445.\overline{6}$. Hence, $n=\boxed{13446}$.

Repeatedly applying long division, we see that

\begin{align*}
\left\lfloor \frac{5^{2017015}}{5^{2015}+7} \right\rfloor &= 5^{2017015-2015} - \frac{7 \cdot 5^{2017015-2015}}{5^{2015}+7} \\ &= 5^{2017015-2015} - 7 \cdot 5^{2017015-2 \cdot 2015} + \frac{7^2 \cdot 5^{2017015-2 \cdot 2015}}{5^{2015}+7} \\ &\vdots \\ &= 5^{2017015 - 2015} - 7 \cdot 5^{2017015 - 2\cdot 2015} + \cdots  + 7^{1000} - \frac{7^{1001}}{5^{2015} + 7} 
\end{align*}Therefore, $\left\lfloor \frac{5^{2017015}}{5^{2015}+7} \right\rfloor \equiv -1 + \sum_{k=0}^{1000} (-7)^{1000-k} \cdot 5^{2015k} \pmod{100}$. Clearly this is equivalent to $7^{1000} - 1 \equiv 1-1 \equiv 0 \pmod{125}$ and $-1+ \sum_{k=0}^{1000} 5^{2015k} \equiv -1 +\sum_{k=0}^{1000} 5^{6k} \equiv -1 + 1001 \equiv 0 \pmod{8}$. Hence, the desired answer is $\boxed{0}$.

