It's easy to see that Shaq obtains the largest number when he repeatedly preforms the operation on the two largest numbers currently on the board. Note that $[a,b] = ab-a-b = (a-1)(b-1)-1$ so

\begin{align*}
V &= [ \cdots [[[100,99],98],97], \cdots ], 2] \\ &= \left( \cdots \left(\left(\left(\left(\left(\left(\left(101-1\right)\left(100-1\right)-1\right)-1\right)\left(99-1\right)-1\right)-1\right)\left(98-1\right)-1\right)-1\right) \cdots \right) -1\\ &= \left( \cdots \left(\left(\left(\left(\left(\left(100\cdot99-1\right)-1\right)\cdot98-1\right)-1\right)\cdot97-1\right)-1\right) \cdots \right) -1 \\ &= \left( \cdots \left(\left(\left(100\cdot99-2\right)\cdot98-2\right)\cdot97-2\right) \cdots \right) -1 \\ &= 100!-2\left(98!+97!+\cdots+1!\right)-1
\end{align*}Clearly $N=100$ so we wish to find the integer closes to

\begin{align*}
10^6\cdot2\cdot\left(\frac{1}{100\cdot99}+\frac{1}{100\cdot99\cdot98}+\frac{1}{100\cdot99\cdot97\cdot96}+\cdots+\frac{1}{100!}\right)-\frac{1}{100!}
\end{align*}which we can approximate as $10^6\cdot2\cdot\left(\frac{1}{100\cdot99}+\frac{1}{100\cdot99\cdot98}\right) \approx 202+2 = \boxed{204}$.

Notice that

\begin{align*}
f\left(x\right)-f\left(\tfrac{1}{x}\right) &= \sum_{a\ge 0} \sum_{b \ge  0} \frac{x^{2^a3^b}}{1-x^{6\cdot2^a3^b}}-\frac{x^{-2^a3^b}}{1-x^{-6\cdot2^a3^b}} \\ &=\sum_{a\ge 0} \sum_{b \ge  0}\frac{\left(x^{2^a3^b}+x^{5\cdot2^a3^b}\right)\left(1-x^{-6\cdot2^a3^b}\right)}{\left(1-x^{6\cdot2^a3^b}\right)\left(1-x^{-6\cdot2^a3^b}\right)} \\ &= \sum_{a\ge 0} \sum_{b \ge  0} \frac{x^{2^a3^b}\cdot\left(1+x^{4\cdot2^a3^b}\right)}{1-x^{6\cdot2^a3^b}} \\&=\sum_{a\ge 0} \sum_{b \ge  0}  \left(1+x^{4\cdot2^a3^b}\right)\sum_{c\ge0}x^{\left(6c+1\right)\cdot2^a3^b} \\ &= \sum_{a\ge 0} \sum_{b \ge  0} \left(\sum_{c\ge0}^{ }x^{\left(6c+1\right)\cdot2^a3^b}+\sum_{c\ge0}^{ }x^{\left(6c+5\right)\cdot2^a3^b}\right) \\ &= \sum_{a\ge 0} \sum_{m \ge  0} x^{2^a \cdot (2m+1)} \\ &= \sum_{n > 0} x^n \\ &= \frac{x}{x-1}
\end{align*}Hence, $\tfrac{y}{y-1} = 2016$ so $y = \tfrac{2016}{2017} \implies p+q = \boxed{4033}$.

Y by Adventure10, Mango247Rearranging the condition gives $ab+bc-ac=1$ or $b=\frac{ac-1}{a+c}$. Thus we can substitute $a=\tan(x)$, $b=-\cot (x+y)$, $c=\tan(y)$.



Then the expression we wish to maximize is

\begin{align*}
4\cos ^2 (x) + 4 \sin ^2(x+y) + 7 \cos ^2 (y) & = 2\cos (2x)+2-2\cos (2x+2y)+2+\frac{7}{2} \cos (2y)+\frac{7}{2} \\
& = 2(\cos (2x) - \cos (2x+2y)) + \frac{7}{2} \cos (2y) + \frac{15}{2} \\
& = 4\sin (2x+y) \sin (y) + \frac{7}{2} \cos (2y) + \frac{15}{2}
\end{align*}

It is obvious that we can choose a suitable $x$ for every $y$ such that $\sin (2x+y)=1$, so we can ignore it and focus only on $y$.

Using the cosine double angle formula gives this expression is equal to $-7 \sin ^2(y) + 4 \sin (y) + 11$, which has a maximum at $\sin (y) = \frac{2}{7}$.

Substituting gives a maximum of $\frac{81}{7}$, so the answer is $\boxed{88}$.

